BBVA, Santander, Espirito Santo, Mota-Engil: Iberian Preview

-- B y   B e n   S i l l s   a n d   M a n u e l   B a i g o r r i
-- 
2011-03-17T07:44:50Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-16/bbva-banco-espirito-santo-mota-engil-iberian-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes in Spanish and Portuguese trading. Stock
symbols are in parentheses and share prices are from the
previous close.  Spain’s  IBEX 35 Index (IBEX)  slid 2.3 percent to 10,092.60.
Portugal’s  PSI-20 Index (PSI20)  fell 1 percent to 7,792.85.  Spanish stocks:    Banco Bilbao Vizcaya Argentaria SA (BBVA)  : Spain’s
second largest bank said in a filing its scrip dividend program
would be implemented in April with shareholders having until
April 11 to say if they want to be remunerated in cash.  Separately, BBVA will create an automobile credit company
in Peru as it seeks to profit from what the bank forecasts will
be Latin America’s fastest-growing market for car loans. The
shares lost 4 percent to 8.54 euros.    Banco Santander SA (SAN)  : The Mexican unit of Banco
Santander will sell as much as 6 billion pesos of variable-rate
bonds maturing in two years, the company said in a statement to
Mexico’s stock exchange. The shares dropped 3.2 percent to 8.03
euros.    Bankinter SA (BKT)  : The Spanish lender, which will sell
as much as 406 million euros of convertible bonds in two
tranches, has set the conversion price of the bonds into shares,
according to a regulatory filing. The shares sank 3.8 percent to
4.71 euros.    Grifols SA (GRF)  : Europe’s largest maker of blood-plasma
products is among the companies with “best scope for share
price recovery,” according to JPMorgan Chase & Co. The shares
climbed 1.2 percent to 11.88 euros.  Portuguese stocks:    Banco Espirito Santo SA (BES)  ,  Banco Comercial Portugues
SA (BCP)  : Portugal’s biggest banks may be active after the
Finance Ministry said it does not foresee a need to increase
banks’ capital with government funds. Espirito Santo shares lost
2.6 percent to 3.14 euros. BCP shares slipped 1.3 percent to
63.4 euro cents.    Mota-Engil SGPS SA (EGL)  : Portugal’s biggest
construction company is scheduled to announce full-year
earnings. The shares lost 2.7 percent to 1.93 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Ben Sills in Madrid at   bsills@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Reed Landberg at   landberg@bloomberg.net  